==Production==
''The Future is Wild'' is a £5-million co-production of the [[British Broadcasting Corporation]] (BBC), the Franco-German channel [[Arte]], the German [[ZDF]], the Austrian [[ORF (broadcaster)|ORF]], the Italian [[Mediaset]], and [[Animal Planet]] and [[Discovery Channel|Discovery Channels Inc]] of the United States.<ref name="zdf">{{cite web|last=Mainz|title=''The Future is Wild'' is ZDF Enterprises’ bestselling documentary in 2003|url=http://enterprise-test.zdf.de/en/the_future_is_wild_is_zdf_enterprises’_bestselling_documentary_in_2003.2094.htm|publisher=ZDF Enterprises|accessdate=19 October 2011|date=26 November 2003}} {{Dead link|date=July 2017}}</ref>

The BBC intended that the miniseries would repeat the success it had with its prehistoric documentary series ''[[Walking With Dinosaurs]]'', which attracted 17 million viewers in 1999. The program used [[computer-generated imagery]] to show the possible future of [[life|life on Earth]]. The 13-part series was produced in four years by independent producer John Adams, who conceived it in 1997.<ref name=fish>{{cite news|last=Byrne|first=Ciar|title=Fish in trees and elephant-sized squid - the future as seen on TV|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/fish-in-trees-and-elephantsized-squid--the-future-as-seen-on-tv-568162.html|accessdate=19 October 2011|newspaper=The Independent|date=30 March 2004}} {{Dead link|date=July 2017}}</ref>

===Scientists involved===
Scientists involved in the project include the following:
* [[Robert McNeill Alexander]], [[zoologist]]
* [[Leticia Aviles]], [[evolutionary biology|evolutionary biologist]]
* [[Philip J. Currie|Phillip Currie]], [[paleontologist]] and [[paleoornithologist]] (the study of prehistoric birds)
* [[Dougal Dixon]], [[geologist]]
* [[Richard Fortey]], [[paleontologist]]
* [[William Gilly]], [[cell biologist]], [[developmental biologist]] and [[marine biologist]]
* [[Stephen Harris (mammalogist)|Stephen Harris]], [[mammalogist]]
* [[Kurt Kotrschal]], [[zoologist]]
* [[Mike Linley]], [[herpetologist]]
* [[Roy Livermore]], [[palaeogeographer]]
* [[R. McNeill Alexander]], specialist in [[biomechanics]]
* [[Karl J. Niklas]], [[botanist]]
* [[Stephen Palumbi]], [[marine biologist]]
* [[Jeremy Rayner]], [[zoologist]]
* [[Robert Stephen John Sparks]], [[geologist]]
* [[Bruce H. Tiffney]], [[palaeobotanist]]
* [[Paul Valdes]], [[Paleoclimatology|paleoclimatologist]]

==Distribution==

''The Future is Wild'' doubled the previous ratings record for the Animal Planet channel when it was aired in the United States. The series was shown on BBC2 in late 2004.<ref name=fish />

ZDF Enterprises sold the television rights of the series to 18 markets: Belgium, Canada, Croatia, the Czech Republic, Ecuador, France, Germany, Hong Kong, Hungary, Japan, Korea, Mexico, the Middle East, Poland, Romania, Russia, Slovenia and Venezuela.<ref name="zdf" />

==Merchandise==

===DVD release===
The series was released on three DVDs: episodes 1–5, episodes 6–9 and episodes 10–13. The three DVDs have also been released together as a set. Both the single DVDs and the three-DVD set are available for [[DVD regions]] one and two. Although the singles are available for region four, the three-DVD set is not. In addition to the complete edition, there is also an abridged region 2  3-disc version which condenses each of the three time periods into one 52-minute episode.

===CD-ROM===
An educational CD-ROM entitled ''The Future Is Wild'' was produced by [[Sherston Software]] in 2006. It is designed to fit in with international school curricula for science, mathematics, geography and history.

===Book===
A book version was released in 2003, published by Firefly Books.

===Futuroscope===

In 2008-2012 [[Futuroscope]] theme park in [[Poitiers]], France contained an exhibit dedicated to the movie, its animals and habitats.

Since 2016 [http://www.dinosaurierpark-teufelsschlucht.de/eo/cms?_SID=badf4f21b7f6c08177f4529cb1d45f0f5ffac28c00255764268926&_template_variant3=%2F100062%2F100085&_sprache=dinopark&_bereich=artikel&_aktion=detail&idartikel=102802 Dinosaurier Park Teufelsschlucht] in [[Ernzen, Germany|Ernzen]] has displayed multiple animals from the series. 

